message.content: A bell_cote is a small tower or structure that is often added to the roof or facade of a building to house a bell or bells. This architectural feature is typically constructed from brick, stone, or wood, and can be found in various shapes and sizes depending on the overall architecture of the building. Bell_cotes are often ornately decorated with intricate carvings, moldings, and embellishments, and may be painted or finished in a variety of colors and textures. They are commonly used in religious buildings such as churches and cathedrals, as well as in public buildings such as schools and town halls. Bell_cotes are primarily used to house bells that are rung to announce the time, call people to worship, or signal important events in the community. They are usually situated in a prominent location on the building so that the sound of the bells can be heard throughout the surrounding area.
